📘 SOP: Splunk Universal Forwarder GUID Remediation

Applies to: Linux and Windows servers
Purpose: Ensure each Splunk Universal Forwarder (UF) has a unique GUID to prevent duplicate reporting and dropped connections in Splunk Cloud.

1️⃣ Background

The Splunk Universal Forwarder generates a GUID (Globally Unique Identifier) on first startup and stores it in:

Linux:
/opt/splunkforwarder/etc/instance.cfg

Windows:
C:\Program Files\SplunkUniversalForwarder\etc\instance.cfg

If servers are cloned from a golden image after Splunk has already started, multiple servers may share the same GUID.

This can cause:

Dropped forwarder connections

Incorrect host reporting

Data ingestion inconsistencies

Duplicate asset conflicts

2️⃣ When to Perform This Remediation

Perform GUID remediation if:

Multiple servers report the same GUID

Splunk team identifies duplicate GUIDs

Server was cloned from an image with Splunk pre-installed

During AMI hardening process (recommended best practice)

3️⃣ Pre-Change Requirements

Approved change request (if production)

Confirm server is reporting to Splunk

Confirm maintenance window (if required)

4️⃣ GUID Remediation – Linux
Step 1: Verify current GUID
cat /opt/splunkforwarder/etc/instance.cfg

Document the existing GUID.

Step 2: Stop Splunk Forwarder

If systemd-managed:

systemctl stop SplunkForwarder

If not systemd-managed:

/opt/splunkforwarder/bin/splunk stop
Step 3: Remove instance.cfg
rm -f /opt/splunkforwarder/etc/instance.cfg
Step 4: Start Splunk Forwarder

If systemd-managed:

systemctl start SplunkForwarder

If not:

/opt/splunkforwarder/bin/splunk start
Step 5: Validate new GUID
cat /opt/splunkforwarder/etc/instance.cfg

Confirm:

A new GUID is generated

It differs from the previous value

5️⃣ GUID Remediation – Windows
Step 1: Verify current GUID

PowerShell (Run as Administrator):

Get-Content "C:\Program Files\SplunkUniversalForwarder\etc\instance.cfg"

Document the existing GUID.

Step 2: Stop Splunk Service
Stop-Service SplunkForwarder

Verify stopped:

Get-Service SplunkForwarder
Step 3: Remove instance.cfg
Remove-Item "C:\Program Files\SplunkUniversalForwarder\etc\instance.cfg"
Step 4: Start Splunk Service
Start-Service SplunkForwarder
Step 5: Validate new GUID
Get-Content "C:\Program Files\SplunkUniversalForwarder\etc\instance.cfg"

Confirm new GUID is generated.

6️⃣ Post-Validation in Splunk Cloud

Confirm server is reporting:

(index=linux OR index=windows)
host="<hostname>"
| stats count by host

Optional: Validate no duplicate GUIDs:

index=_internal sourcetype=splunkd
| rex "guid=(?<guid>[A-Fa-f0-9-]+)"
| stats dc(forwarder) as forwarder_count values(forwarder) by guid
| where forwarder_count > 1
7️⃣ Golden Image Best Practice (IMPORTANT)

When building AMIs or templates:

Recommended approach:

Install Splunk Universal Forwarder

Configure deployment server / outputs

Before creating image, run:

Linux:

rm -f /opt/splunkforwarder/etc/instance.cfg

Windows:

Remove-Item "C:\Program Files\SplunkUniversalForwarder\etc\instance.cfg"

Shutdown instance

Create image

This ensures each new server generates its own GUID at first boot.


